data.title: Weezer wows 'em
data.meta_description: If you were to look up “unassuming rock star” in a dictionary you would find Weezer's Rivers Cuomo.
data.text:
Article content

Orillia

If you were to look up “unassuming rock star” in a dictionary you would find Weezer's Rivers Cuomo.

Midway through the band's stellar 20-song, 80-minute set at a near-capacity Casino Rama, Cuomo and his band mates named some of the bands whose photos they noticed along the venue's walls, with Cuomo citing KISS. But while Gene Simmons would be recognized for many things, Cuomo ventured out onstage just before the set to test his guitar as hardly anybody noticed who it was.

The only similarities between the two might be their light show, with “KISS” often in huge lettering behind Simmons and a “W” in lights behind drummer Patrick Wilson.

Regardless, Weezer's knack for creating simple but incredibly infectious power pop was in full force Friday night beginning with My Name Is Jonas as the aisles and front of stage quickly filled up with energized fans. Cuomo, looking suited for an autumnal trek through the woods with his jacket and sweater, kept the vibe throughout with the meaty Hash Pipe the first of many highlights.

Following Memories which came off like a fine punchy romp, Cuomo handed the vocal duties off to guitarist Brian Bell for Keep Fishin', better known as the “Muppet video” song to many. Here the bespectacled Cuomo did some fist bumps with those standing near the stage before returning to the microphone for We Are All On Drugs.

Ridiculously tight musically from start to finish and the venue's fine acoustics only enhancing that trademark, Weezer tore through its set with hardly any downtime. Fans belted out most of the numbers like the chipper, bouncy (If You're Wondering If I Want You To) I Want You To and Dope Nose which caused a huge sing-along. Cuomo gave kudos to bassist Scott Shriner for his lead vocal on Dope Nose, creating an impromptu song about Shriner before the summery, breezy Island In The Sun soared.

Perhaps the show highlight was during Troublemaker as Cuomo – feeling the “body heat” -- sat on the lip of the stage before sauntering through the crowd, met with a slew of back slaps and rigorous hugs from some diehard fans. A few songs later Weezer would up the ante with the delightful Buddy Holly from their self-titled album.

Wait, they have three self-titled albums, but Buddy Holly is from their 1994 debut best known as The Blue Album.

After citing the stars who played Casino Rama like Don Rickles, Boston, Billy Squier and Tim Conway, Weezer began their crowd-pleasing homestretch with El Scorcho and the rudimentary but rousing Beverly Hills. Meanwhile The Greatest Man That Ever Lived (Variations On A Shaker Hymn) ran the genre gamut from rap to rockabilly to Beach Boys-like harmonies as Cuomo donned a wide-brimmed cowboy hat, briefly becoming Garth Cuomo.

Citing that they were leaving shortly to get on the bus for a show in another town (Baltimore) on Saturday night, Weezer closed the proceedings with a two-song encore, the beefy Pork And Beans and the slower Say It Ain't So. Many fans were probably hoping it wasn't the end, but with a consistently solid setlist offered on this night nobody left shortchanged.
